          <source>CAtlServiceModuleT::Handler Function</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>is the routine that the service control manager (SCM) calls to retrieve the status of the service and give it various instructions (such as stopping or pausing).</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The SCM passes an operation code to <ph id="ph1">`Handler`</ph> to indicate what the service should do.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A default ATL-generated service only handles the stop instruction.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>If the SCM passes the stop instruction, the service tells the SCM that the program is about to stop.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The service then calls <ph id="ph1">`PostThreadMessage`</ph> to post a quit message to itself.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>This terminates the message loop and the service will ultimately close.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>To handle more instructions, you need to change the <ph id="ph1">`m_status`</ph> data member initialized in the <ph id="ph2">`CAtlServiceModuleT`</ph> constructor.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>This data member tells the SCM which buttons to enable when the service is selected in the Services Control Panel application.</source>
        </trans-unit>
